{"questionId":"9083940","questionHtml":"<p>A student quotes three equations related to atomic and nuclear physics:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\">I.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mtext>eV</mtext></math></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\">II.&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>λ</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\">III.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>Which equations refer to the Bohr model for hydrogen?</p>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp; I and II only</p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; I and III only</p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; II and III only</p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; I, II and III</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>B</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9083940","referenceCode":"22N.1A.HL.TZ0.38","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"A student quotes three equations related to atomic and nuclear physics: I. E=-13.6n2eV II. N=N0e-λt III. mvr=nh2π Which equations refer to the Bohr model for hydrogen? A. I and II ","paper":"1A","level":"HL","questionNumber":"38","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E.1 Structure of the atom"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}